The Open Source Transparency License (OSTL) v1.0

Copyright (c) 2026 Vince Shields

This is free and unencumbered software released into the public domain.

Anyone is free to copy, modify, publish, use, compile, sell, or distribute this
software, either in source code form or as a compiled binary, for any purpose,
commercial or non-commercial, and by any means.


Permission is hereby granted, free of charge, to any person obtaining a copy of
this software and associated documentation files (the "Software"), to use, copy,
modify, merge, publish, distribute, sublicense, and sell copies of the
Software, and to permit persons to whom the Software is furnished to do so,
subject to the following conditions:

1. Retention of Notice

The above copyright notice and this license must be retained in all copies or
substantial portions of the Software, whether in source or binary form.

2. Commercial Transparency Obligation

Any party that engages in any of the following activities:

- Selling the Software directly, in whole or in part
- Selling a product or service in which the Software constitutes a substantial
  or material component
- Charging a fee for access to the Software, including via subscription,
  licensing fee, or software-as-a-service arrangement

must comply with all of the following:

(a) Point-of-Sale Notice.
Prior to or at the moment of purchase, the purchaser must be clearly informed,
in plain language, that the Software or a component thereof is available free
of charge under an open source license. This notice must not be buried in fine
print, terms of service, or end-user license agreements. It must appear in a
location and font size reasonably comparable to the pricing information.

(b) Access Information.
The notice required in (a) must include a functioning URL or clearly described
means by which the purchaser may obtain the Software at no cost. This URL or
description must remain accurate and accessible for the duration of the
commercial offering.

(c) Scope of Notice.
The notice must accurately represent which portions of the product are covered
by this license. It is not sufficient to state that "some open source
components are used" without identifying the Software by name.

(d) No Misrepresentation.
The selling party must not make representations, whether explicit or implied,
that suggest the Software itself — apart from any value-added services,
support, or modifications — is proprietary, exclusive, or unavailable
elsewhere.

3. Value-Added Services Exemption

Nothing in Section 2 prohibits a party from charging for support, installation,
customization, managed hosting, training, or other services rendered in
connection with the Software, provided that the Software itself is clearly
identified as freely available per Section 2(a).

4. Modifications

Modified versions of the Software may be distributed under different license
terms, provided that:

- The original, unmodified Software remains obtainable at no cost as required
  by Section 2
- The modified portions are clearly distinguished from the original Software
- The notice required by Section 2 accurately distinguishes between the freely
  available original and any proprietary modifications

5. No Warranty

The Software is provided "as is," without warranty of any kind, express or
implied, including but not limited to warranties of merchantability, fitness
for a particular purpose, or noninfringement. In no event shall the author or
copyright holders be liable for any claim, damages, or other liability, whether
in an action of contract, tort, or otherwise, arising from, out of, or in
connection with the Software or the use or other dealings in the Software.

6. Definitions

"Substantial or material component" means the Software provides core or
significant functionality to the product, such that removing it would
meaningfully impair the product's primary purpose.

"Selling party" means any individual, organization, or legal entity engaging in
the commercial activities described in Section 2.

"Point of sale" means any webpage, screen, document, or interaction at which a
purchasing decision is made or a transaction is initiated.
